{"text": "====== [46.5] Electron in Hall geometry: The Landau states\n\nWe go back to the Hamiltonian that describes the motion of a particle in the Hall bar geometry (see beginning\n\nof previous section). Recall that we have periodic boundary conditions in the x axis, and an arbitrary confining\n\npotential V (y) in the y direction. We would like to find the eigenstates and the eigenvalues of the Hamiltonian. The\n\nkey observation is that in the Landau gauge the momentum operator px is a constant of motion. It is more physical\n\nto re-phrase this statement in a gauge independent way. Namely, the constant of motion is in fact\n\nY\n\n=\n\n\u02c6y \u22121\n\n\u03c9B\n\n\u02c6vx\n\n=\n\n\u22121\n\nB \u02c6px\n\n(46.26)\n\nwhich represents the y location of the classical cycloid. In fact the eigenstates that we are going to find are the\n\nquantum mechanical analogue of the classical cycloids. The eigenvalues of \u02c6px are 2\u03c0/Lx \u00d7 integer. Equivalently, we\n\nmay write that the eigenvalues of \u02c6Y are:\n\nYl\n\n=\n\n2\u03c0\n\nBLx\n\nl,\n\n[l= integer]\n\n(46.27)\n\nThat means that the y distance between the eigenstates is quantized.\n\nAccording to the \u201dseparation of variables\n\ntheorem\u201d the Hamiltonian matrix is a block diagonal matrix in the basis in which the \u02c6Y matrix is diagonal. It is\n\nnatural to choose the basis l, y\u27e9which is determined by the operators \u02c6px,\n\n\u02c6y.\n\n\u27e8l, y H l\u2032, y\u2032\u27e9\n\n=\n\n\u03b4l,l\u2032 Hl\n\nyy\u2032\n\n(46.28)\n\nIt is convenient to write the Hamiltonian of the block lin abstract notation (without indexes):\n\nHl\n\n=\n\n1\n\n2m \u02c6p2\n\ny + B2\n\n2m(\u02c6y \u2212Yl)2 + V (\u02c6y)\n\n(46.29)\n\nOr, in another notation:\n\nHl\n\n=\n\n1\n\n2m \u02c6p2\n\ny + Vl(\u02c6y)\n\n(46.30)\n\nwhere the effective potential is:\n\nVl(y)\n\n=\n\nV (y) + 1\n\n2m\u03c92\n\nB(y \u2212Yl)2\n\n(46.31)\n\nFor a given l, we find the eigenvalues l, \u03bd\u27e9of the one-dimensional Hamiltonian Hl. The running index \u03bd = 0, 1, 2, 3, . . .\n\nindicates the quantized values of the kinetic energy.\n\nFor a constant electric field we notice that this is the Schr \u0308odinger equation of a displaced harmonic oscillator.", "embedding": [0.014514801, -0.005622894, 0.044104088, 0.00041763834, 0.0048356554, -0.0105083, 0.02377479, -0.017102905, -0.04764669, 0.035438895, 0.026235234, 0.027067587, -0.0089837015, -0.0554725, -0.0091245575, 0.023276813, -0.007906197, -0.025319366, -0.07885204, 0.056045294, 0.033540137, 0.0117932465, -0.07241174, -0.016512658, -0.010016858, 0.029411618, 0.03027486, 0.03324257, 0.039233495, 0.054149043, 0.048956748, -0.01755266, 0.012319179, -0.041295834, 0.0033637485, 0.019213729, -0.012024411, -0.043044675, 0.027385684, -0.02551056, 0.034179647, -0.024812572, 0.008755007, 0.021621991, -0.03507827, -0.028236147, -0.0070308847, 0.009640956, 0.0048494106, -0.07921259, 0.0041730697, 0.0008284185, 0.05375589, -0.010095599, -0.010739105, -0.015927197, 0.00024635764, 0.009757065, -0.040879387, 0.031590674, -0.00049265067, -0.018796949, 0.014832699, -0.041918676, 0.005420979, 0.015101287, 0.0082461005, 0.023805743, -0.010243483, -0.047709487, -0.0015911972, 0.002691648, -0.035817556, 0.0028050903, -0.063878626, 0.037072036, -0.02672546, -0.01524395, -0.046615336, -0.031593636, -0.013539824, -0.019943811, -0.0047061793, 0.044614244, -0.0234622, -0.0044990564, -0.0020040288, -0.024446413, 0.027819825, -0.01695789, 0.024643108, 0.05962272, 0.004200644, -0.0038896555, 0.060598176, 0.039201666, -0.0022499752, 0.048236266, 0.06286989, 0.008134632, 0.0048289457, 0.054417256, -0.019273292, 0.049116842, -0.028156642, 0.05840384, -0.011316596, 0.018343471, -0.021854185, -0.047155183, 0.012455693, -0.017679015, 0.032286678, 0.030641994, -0.0078114825, 0.026474135, 0.01500133, -0.0076606246, -0.028119797, -0.015222732, 0.021128608, -0.011890417, 0.0445614, 0.014246026, -0.030247755, -0.013589392, -0.0022721111, 0.009121885, -0.04397834, 0.0